6","Whitmore, Staffordshire, England":"Whitmore, Staffordshire, England","Whitmore, Newcastle-under-Lyme, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whitmore, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Market Drayton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Market Drayton, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Thurstaston, Cheshire, England":"Thurstaston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Thurstan, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1420–1510":"1420–1510","1406–1460":"1406–1460","1434–1480":"1434–1480","1439–1520":"1439–1520","1377–1429":"1377–1429","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1434":"1434","1510":"1510","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1520":"1520","1420":"1420","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1429":"1429","1380":"1380","1439":"1439","1406":"1406","Whitmore, Staffordshire, England":"Whitmore, Staffordshire, England","Whitmore, Newcastle-under-Lyme, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whitmore, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Market Drayton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Market Drayton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Thurstaston, Cheshire, England":"Thurstaston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Thurstan, Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Grosvenor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from French <i>gros</i> ‘big, great’ + <i>veneur</i> ‘hunter’.","History: This is the name of one of the wealthiest families in Britain, which holds the title Duke of Westminster. They have been long established in Cheshire, with strong links with the city of Chester. One of the earliest recorded bearers of the name was Robert le Grosvenor of Budworth, who was granted lands by the Earl of Chester in 1160. The family's fortunes were founded by Thomas Grosvenor (born 1656), who in 1677 married an heiress, Mary Davies, whose inheritance included Ebury Farm, Middlesex. This now forms an area of central London that includes Grosvenor Square and Belgrave Square."],"variants":[{"name":"Gravenor","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>grand</i> ‘big, tall’ + <i>veneor</i> ‘hunter’. Compare   Grosvenor  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":35,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Grosvenor was born in 1420, in Staffordshire, England, her father, Thomas GROSVENOR, was 43 and her mother, Katherine Fesant, was 40. She had at least 2 daughters with Richard de Whitmore. She died in 1510, in Whitmore, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 90."},"et":{"1420–1510":"1420–1510","1406–1460":"1406–1460","1434–148